<CaseStudyLayout title="Category Intelligence for Two Opposite Markets: Lighting and E-STATCOM">
  <h1>Category Intelligence for Two Opposite Markets: Lighting and E-STATCOM</h1>

  <div class="cs-spec">
    <div><p class="k">Functional Topic</p><p class="v">Category Intelligence, Cost-Driver Analysis & Supply Market Strategy</p></div>
    <div><p class="k">Industry</p><p class="v">Energy & Utilities · Industrial Procurement</p></div>
    <div><p class="k">Support Needed</p><p class="v">Category Intelligence & Market Briefing Consultant</p></div>
    <div><p class="k">Duration</p><p class="v">8 Weeks</p></div>
  </div>

  <h2>The Challenge</h2>
  <p>The client needed category intelligence ahead of sourcing decisions across two categories that could not be more different: Lighting (LED luminaires — high volume, many suppliers, commoditizing) and E-STATCOM (grid reactive-power compensation — engineered, few suppliers, demand surging with renewable integration). The team lacked:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>A consolidated view of market size, growth, and supplier concentration for either category.</li>
    <li>Visibility into the cost-driver structure — what actually moves price, and therefore where prices are heading.</li>
    <li>A differentiated sourcing posture: both categories were being approached identically despite opposite supply dynamics.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>My Role</h2>
  <p>I led the category intelligence assessment and the market briefings to client stakeholders across both categories — defining one intelligence framework (market structure, cost drivers, price outlook, supply risk), building the cost-driver breakdowns and price outlook, mapping each supplier landscape, and translating findings into a differentiated sourcing posture.</p>

  <h2>The Approach</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Scope and segment</strong> — defined each category's boundaries and the buying decisions the intelligence needed to inform.</li>
    <li><strong>Map the supply market</strong> — sized each market, mapped the supplier landscape, and measured concentration.</li>
    <li><strong>Decompose cost</strong> — built a should-cost-style cost-driver breakdown for each category.</li>
    <li><strong>Build the price outlook</strong> — linked cost drivers to leading indices to form a directional outlook.</li>
    <li><strong>Set posture & brief</strong> — translated into a differentiated sourcing strategy and briefed stakeholders.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>The Analysis</h2>

